\begin{abstract}
Children with Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) face significant barriers to communication, structured learning, and emotional self-awareness — barriers that are compounded in the Indian context by the absence of bilingual, locally contextualised assistive tools. This paper presents the design, architecture, and expert evaluation of a native Android application that addresses these gaps by integrating six functional modules within a single sensory-aware interface: a tile-based Augmentative and Alternative Communication (AAC) grid organised using the Fitzgerald Key colour-coding standard; a bilingual sentence-builder engine that handles the grammatical divergence between English Subject-Verb-Object and Kannada Subject-Object-Verb ordering; an Augmented Reality vocabulary pipeline powered by Google ARCore and ML Kit that anchors AAC word cards to detected real-world objects; an on-device emotion recognition module built on a MobileNetV3 model trained on the IIITM Face Emotion dataset; a caregiver personalisation system enabling parents to create custom vocabulary tiles from real photographs; and a gamified quiz-based assessment module with role-differentiated progress tracking for therapists and students. The system was developed following a design thinking methodology grounded in empathy fieldwork at two specialised ASD centres in Bengaluru. Structured expert feedback sessions demonstrated qualitative improvements in engagement, participation, and communicative initiative. The work represents the first demonstration of this combination of capabilities in a single deployable application designed for the Indian ASD context.
\end{abstract}

