\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Background and Motivation}

Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) is a neurodevelopmental condition that affects how children communicate, process sensory information, and engage with the world around them. What makes ASD particularly complex is the sheer variability in how it manifests --- no two children experience it in the same way. Some struggle primarily with verbal communication, others with sensory regulation, and many face simultaneous challenges across both dimensions. This heterogeneity means that a one-size-fits-all educational approach is not merely ineffective but actively harmful to a child's developmental trajectory.

The scale of the problem is striking. Globally, approximately 1 in 36 children are on the autism spectrum, and India alone is estimated to have around 18 million individuals with ASD, according to NIMHANS (2022). Despite these numbers, more than 70\% of autistic children in India lack access to either technology-aided or professionally specialised education. Most rely on conventional classroom instruction designed for neurotypical learners --- an environment that rarely accommodates the visual, repetitive, and sensory-aware learning style that many autistic children respond to best.

This gap matters acutely because the developmental window between ages five and eight is widely recognised as the most critical period for building foundational literacy and numeracy skills. Interventions introduced during this window tend to produce lasting cognitive gains, whereas delays compound over time. Research further supports what many therapists have observed in practice: visual and interactive learning strategies improve information retention in autistic learners by as much as 40\% compared to traditional didactic methods~\cite{b1}.

Technology-assisted learning has also demonstrated significant benefits for improving engagement, communication, and learning outcomes among children with ASD~\cite{b7,b8,b19,b23}. Recent advances in assistive technologies emphasize the importance of integrating communication support, visual learning, and personalized educational interventions within a unified platform to maximize developmental outcomes.

Yet the tools that could deliver this kind of structured, visual, interactive instruction remain out of reach for the majority of families in the Indian context --- either because they are too expensive, too complex for caregivers to operate without specialist training, or simply not designed with the sensory sensitivities and communication profiles of Indian autistic children in mind.

Our team undertook an in-depth empathy phase to understand these challenges from multiple perspectives. We engaged with medical professionals, special educators, occupational therapists, and parents across two specialised centres --- the Pragyan CDC Center in Nagarbhavi and the Sambhavam Center for Autism, Bengaluru. Dr.~Sahana from Pragyan CDC highlighted the clinical importance of Augmentative and Alternative Communication (AAC) for non-verbal and minimally verbal children, pointing specifically to the absence of a bilingual AAC solution suited to the Indian linguistic context. Therapists at Sambhavam described how sensory meltdowns could be pre-empted by carefully designed environments, and how pairing children with peers of similar age groups measurably improved communication. Parents, meanwhile, expressed a practical concern that runs through every conversation about assistive technology: they need something simple enough to use at home, clearly effective, and affordable.

From these conversations, a coherent need statement emerged. Children with ASD in the five-to-eight age range who are non-verbal or minimally verbal, and who are being served by the Indian healthcare and education system, need an application that does four things simultaneously: communicates through visual and auditory reinforcement, bridges the English--Kannada language gap in a grammatically aware way, brings real-world objects into the learning loop through Augmented Reality, and adapts progressively to each child's specific vocabulary and emotional profile. Nothing currently available in the market addresses all four of these needs together.

\subsection{Problem Statement}

Children with Autism Spectrum Disorder face compounding barriers to communication, structured learning, and emotional self-awareness. These barriers are not merely cognitive --- they are also systemic. The tools designed to support autistic learners are overwhelmingly developed for Western, English-speaking contexts, with little accommodation for the multilingual reality of Indian families. Even among the available AAC applications, most treat communication as an isolated skill rather than embedding it within a broader learning and emotional development framework.

Three specific deficiencies characterise the current landscape. First, existing tools lack meaningful personalisation: they provide generic icon libraries that do not reflect the child's actual home environment, which is particularly problematic for autistic learners who often struggle to generalise abstract representations to real-world objects. Second, the absence of bilingual support --- particularly for structurally divergent language pairs like English and Kannada, which differ fundamentally in their subject-object-verb ordering --- means that children educated in regional-language households receive no reinforcement in their primary language. Third, progress remains invisible to caregivers: there is no mechanism for parents or therapists to observe how a child's word acquisition, emotional recognition, or communication fluency is evolving across sessions.

The consequence is a situation in which the children most in need of structured, adaptive, technology-assisted learning are the least well-served by the technology that exists. An accessible, sensory-aware, bilingual, and data-informed application that combines AAC communication support with AR-based real-world learning and on-device emotion recognition represents a gap that this work directly addresses.

\subsection{Objectives}

The design objectives of this system were derived directly from the empathy and define phases of our design thinking process and validated against the expressed needs of therapists, parents, and children observed across both clinical centres. They are:

\begin{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Communication support for non-verbal children:} To provide a tile-based AAC grid that enables non-verbal or minimally verbal children to express fundamental needs and thoughts --- such as requests for food, water, or breaks --- through visual word tiles organised using professional AAC standards including the Fitzgerald Key colour-coding system.

    \item \textbf{Bilingual sentence construction:} To support sentence building in both English and Kannada, with the application handling the grammatical restructuring required by Kannada's Subject-Object-Verb syntax, ensuring that children in regional-language households receive linguistically accurate reinforcement in their native tongue.

    \item \textbf{Real-world object association through AR:} To use Augmented Reality, powered by Google ARCore and ML Kit Object Detection, to allow children to point a device camera at everyday household objects and receive the corresponding AAC vocabulary card overlaid in three-dimensional space, bridging the critical gap between digital symbols and real-world referents.

    \item \textbf{Personalisation through caregiver-created content:} To allow parents and therapists to add custom vocabulary tiles using real photographs of the child's specific environment --- their actual toys, family members, and familiar objects --- rather than generic cartoon icons, addressing the generalisation difficulties common in ASD.

    \item \textbf{Emotion recognition and social-emotional learning:} To integrate an on-device emotion detection module using ML Kit Face Detection, enabling children to identify facial expressions in themselves and others and thereby build social-emotional awareness in a low-pressure, interactive format.

    \item \textbf{Gamified assessment and progress tracking:} To include a quiz-based assessment module with a reward reinforcement system, alongside differentiated login credentials for therapists and students, so that learning progress can be tracked quantitatively across sessions and communicated to caregivers in a structured way.

\end{itemize}

\subsection{Contributions}

The principal contributions of this work are as follows:

\begin{itemize}

    \item A complete, deployable Android application integrating AAC communication, AR-based object-to-word learning, bilingual sentence building, emotion recognition, and gamified assessment within a single sensory-aware interface --- a combination not previously demonstrated in the existing literature for the Indian ASD context.

    \item A bilingual sentence-builder engine that handles the grammatical divergence between English and Kannada (Subject-Verb-Object versus Subject-Object-Verb ordering), enabling children from Kannada-speaking households to receive native-language reinforcement without requiring a separate application.

    \item An AR vocabulary pipeline in which Google ARCore anchors AAC word cards to detected real-world objects in three-dimensional space, with the grammar engine automatically suggesting contextually appropriate verbs (e.g., surfacing ``Eat'' and ``Want'' when an apple is detected), providing a contextually intelligent learning prompt rather than a static label.

    \item A caregiver personalisation system that enables parents to build custom vocabulary tiles from real photographs of their child's environment, with automatic category-based Fitzgerald Key colour assignment, allowing the application vocabulary to grow with the child's specific communicative needs.

    \item Empirical validation of the system through structured feedback sessions with domain experts at two ASD clinical centres in Bengaluru, demonstrating qualitative improvements in engagement, participation, and communicative initiative across tested sessions.

\end{itemize}

