\section{Literature Review}

The design of assistive technology for children with ASD sits at the intersection of several research threads: AAC system design, AR-based educational tools, on-device machine learning for accessibility, and the broader question of how technology can complement rather than replace therapeutic practice. The review below examines each of these areas and identifies the specific gap that the present work addresses.

\subsection{Augmentative and Alternative Communication for ASD}


Recent research has further demonstrated the effectiveness of AAC technologies in supporting communication development and language acquisition among children with ASD~\cite{b7,b8,b9}. Modern AAC systems increasingly focus on personalization, adaptive vocabulary selection, and integration with digital learning environments, reflecting a shift from communication-only tools toward comprehensive educational support platforms.

However, the study's scope was deliberately narrow. It focused exclusively on communication skills and excluded structured academic content such as vocabulary acquisition, object recognition, or curriculum-linked concept learning. The sample of eight participants over three weeks, while producing encouraging results, leaves important questions unanswered about efficacy at scale and across different levels of severity. Crucially, AVAZ lacks bilingual support for regional Indian languages, making it poorly suited to the majority of its potential users in the Indian context. The present work takes AVAZ's communication-first philosophy as a starting point and extends it with structured academic learning modules, real-world AR grounding, and Kannada language support.

