\subsection{Augmented Reality for Social and Communicative Learning}

Khawaja, Banire, and Al-Thani (2022) examined the use of AR-based games to evaluate improvements in social communication skills among children with ASD~\cite{b2}. Their system provided real-time AR feedback during structured interaction tasks and reported significant increases in engagement and attention compared to non-AR control conditions. The study makes a compelling case that the spatial and interactive properties of AR --- the ability to overlay information on the physical world rather than confining it to a flat screen --- are particularly well-suited to the attentional and perceptual profile of many autistic learners.

The limitation the authors themselves acknowledge is the exclusive focus on social skills, with no attempt to extend the AR framework to structured academic content such as spelling, vocabulary matching, or number recognition. The present work builds directly on their finding that AR interaction improves attention and participation, but redirects the AR pipeline toward curriculum-relevant learning objectives rather than social-emotional tasks alone.

\subsection{AR Vocabulary Applications for Mild ASD}

Hashim, Yunus, and Norman (2023) described AReal-Vocab, an AR application tested with six mildly autistic children to evaluate effectiveness in vocabulary acquisition and pronunciation~\cite{b3}. The results were positive across all three measured dimensions --- vocabulary recognition, engagement, and pronunciation accuracy --- with participants consistently preferring the AR condition to traditional card-based flashcard instruction. The study contributed useful design principles: AR vocabulary tools should minimise interface complexity, maximise visual salience, and reinforce word-object associations through repeated, multimodal interaction.

The study's limitations are equally instructive. AReal-Vocab was not aligned to any structured curriculum, meaning that vocabulary selection was ad hoc rather than graded or sequenced. There was no personalisation mechanism, so all children received the same generic vocabulary set regardless of their individual communicative priorities. And the system was monolingual, limiting its applicability to non-English-speaking populations. The present system addresses each of these gaps: vocabulary can be expanded by caregivers to reflect the child's specific environment, the AAC grid is structured using professional Fitzgerald Key categorisation, and the bilingual engine ensures both English and Kannada reinforcement.

\subsection{AR for Motor Skills and Cognitive Development}

Lima Ant\~{a}o et al. (2021) evaluated an AR-based game designed around alphabet letters and numbers, assessing its impact on cognitive performance and motor skill development in children with ASD~\cite{b4}. The game varied task difficulty and measured both touching accuracy and letter-number recognition across sessions. Improvements in motor coordination and cognitive task performance were observed, with the interactive physical component --- requiring children to reach toward and touch AR-overlaid elements --- providing a combined fine-motor and cognitive training effect.

The study noted that improvements in letter and number touching could not be reliably linked to literacy or numeracy progress, suggesting that interaction with AR elements does not automatically translate into academic learning without a structured pedagogical scaffold. This finding directly informed the design of the present work: our AR module does not treat object detection and word overlay as a standalone activity, but integrates it with the AAC sentence-building system so that detected objects immediately connect to the broader vocabulary and sentence-construction framework.

The present application takes the underlying insight --- that AR experiences grounded in real-world semantics are more engaging and meaningful than purely digital ones --- and re-implements it within a stripped-down, autism-friendly interface where visual elements are controlled, predictable, and sensory-aware.

Recent reviews also highlight the growing effectiveness of AR-based educational systems for engagement, visualization, and contextual learning~\cite{b10,b11,b12}. AR technologies have been shown to improve attention span, task participation, and concept retention by enabling learners to interact directly with virtual information anchored within their physical environment.

\subsection{Gamified Learning for ASD}

\subsection{Interactive AR Storytelling and Semantic Scene Understanding}

Li, Li et al. (2023) presented a system for interactive AR storytelling guided by scene semantics, in which narrative content was automatically adapted to align with real-world scene context detected by the AR engine~\cite{b5}. The system demonstrated how AR could move beyond static overlay to generate contextually coherent, dynamic story experiences grounded in the physical environment. The technical sophistication of the scene understanding pipeline was notable, involving real-time semantic parsing to select contextually appropriate character behaviours and narrative branches.

The limitation relevant to the present work is the absence of any accommodation for learners who require simplified, low-stimulus interfaces. The storytelling system was designed for neurotypical users and relied on a high-complexity multi-element display that would likely be cognitively overwhelming for children with ASD, many of whom are hypersensitive to visual complexity. The present application takes the underlying insight --- that AR experiences grounded in real-world semantics are more engaging and meaningful than purely digital ones --- and re-implements it within a stripped-down, autism-friendly interface where visual elements are controlled, predictable, and sensory-aware.

\subsection{Gamified Learning for ASD}

L\'{o}pez-Bouzas (2023) conducted a systematic review of gamified environments and serious games designed for students with ASD~\cite{b6}. The review found consistent evidence that game-based learning improves motivation, task persistence, and generalisation of skills across multiple studies. Crucially, the review identified reward immediacy --- the principle that reinforcing feedback should follow a correct response within seconds --- as the single most impactful design variable across effective gamified interventions. It also highlighted the underexplored potential of combining game-based assessment with structured data capture for therapeutic planning. The present work operationalises both findings: reward animations trigger immediately upon correct quiz responses, and session data is persisted to a therapist-accessible dashboard for longitudinal review.

Recent studies have shown that gamification strategies can significantly improve motivation, participation, and knowledge retention among learners with developmental and educational challenges~\cite{b16,b17}. Immediate positive reinforcement, achievement tracking, and reward-based progression systems have been identified as key factors contributing to improved engagement in technology-assisted interventions.

\subsection{Synthesis and Research Gap}

Taken together, the surveyed literature establishes three important foundations. AAC mobile tools can meaningfully improve communication in non-verbal autistic children~\cite{b1}. AR-based interaction improves engagement, attention, and learning participation across multiple study designs~\cite{b2, b3, b4}. And semantic AR grounding --- connecting digital content to physically detected real-world objects --- represents an underexplored but promising direction for context-aware educational tools~\cite{b5}.

What the literature does not yet offer is a system that integrates all of these elements within a single, deployable application designed specifically for the Indian context: one that combines AAC communication, curriculum-grounded vocabulary, bilingual sentence construction with grammatical awareness, AR-to-physical-world bridging, emotion recognition, caregiver personalisation, and progress tracking. Each of these capabilities has been studied in isolation; none have been brought together in the way the present work proposes. Equally absent is any design work that takes seriously the multilingual reality of Indian families --- the gap between English-language tools and the Kannada-speaking home environments of many of the children who need them most. The present work addresses both the technical integration gap and the localisation gap simultaneously.

