\section{Theory and Conceptual Background}

\subsection{Augmentative and Alternative Communication}

Augmentative and Alternative Communication (AAC) refers to any system of communication used to supplement or replace speech and writing for individuals who cannot rely on these modalities effectively~\cite{b1}. For non-verbal and minimally verbal children with ASD, AAC devices provide a structured channel through which needs, preferences, and ideas can be expressed. The most widely adopted organisational framework within AAC systems is the Fitzgerald Key, a colour-coding scheme that assigns distinct background colours to words based on their grammatical function. Under this convention, green tiles indicate action words, yellow tiles represent people, blue encodes descriptive terms, and orange denotes core vocabulary. The colour-coding allows children to locate words by grammatical role rather than by alphabetical label --- a significant advantage for learners who think visually and who struggle with sequential text-based search.

Picture Exchange Communication Systems (PECS), developed by Frost and Bondy, provide a complementary theoretical foundation. PECS trains children to initiate communication by exchanging a picture card for a desired item, establishing a cause-effect relationship between symbol use and social outcome. The underlying mechanism --- that repeated, reinforced pairing of a symbol with its real-world referent builds communicative intent --- directly informs the design of the tile-based AAC grid in this work. Where PECS relies on physical card exchange, the digital tile grid replaces the physical medium while preserving the symbol-to-referent mapping logic that gives the system its therapeutic efficacy.

\subsection{Augmented Reality as a Learning Medium}

Augmented Reality systems superimpose computer-generated content onto the user's real-world view in real time. Unlike Virtual Reality, which replaces the environment entirely, AR preserves the physical context while enriching it with digital annotations. For children with ASD, who frequently demonstrate stronger responses to concrete visual stimuli than to abstract representations, the grounding of digital content in the physical world offers a theoretically motivated advantage: a word card anchored to an actual apple on the kitchen counter creates a tighter perceptual link between the symbol and the referent than the same card shown on a flat screen in an abstract context.

The present system leverages two components of the Google AR ecosystem. Google ARCore provides the spatial tracking and anchor management layer, allowing word cards to remain attached to detected objects even as the device camera moves. ML Kit's Object Detection and Tracking API provides the computer vision pipeline that identifies and classifies real-world objects in the camera stream. Together, these components implement what we term an \emph{AR vocabulary pipeline}: a continuous loop in which the physical world is parsed for recognisable objects, each detected object is mapped to its corresponding AAC vocabulary entry, and the word card is rendered in three-dimensional space overlaid on the physical object.

The grammar engine layer adds a further dimension: when an object is detected, the system does not merely display a noun label. It also surfaces contextually relevant verbs that commonly co-occur with the detected noun in authentic communication contexts. When an apple is detected, for instance, the words ``Eat'' and ``Want'' are prioritised alongside the label ``Apple.'' This design choice reflects the theoretical position that communication is inherently relational --- that words derive meaning from their contexts of use --- and that a vocabulary tool which presents only isolated labels misses an opportunity to scaffold the relational, sentence-level communication that AAC is ultimately intended to support.

\subsection{Bilingual Language Processing for Structurally Divergent Languages}

English and Kannada differ not only in lexicon but in fundamental syntactic structure. English follows Subject-Verb-Object (SVO) ordering: a child building the sentence ``I want water'' arranges the elements in this sequence. Kannada, by contrast, follows Subject-Object-Verb (SOV) ordering, so the equivalent sentence is structured as ``I water want.'' A na\"{\i}ve translation layer that maps individual words between the two languages without restructuring the constituent order produces grammatically incorrect Kannada output, which may actively confuse or mislead a child receiving reinforcement in both languages simultaneously.

The bilingual sentence-builder engine in this application addresses this challenge through a rule-based SOV reordering layer that operates on the sentence tray before Kannada audio is generated. When the child has assembled a sentence, the engine identifies the subject, object, and verb components of the tile sequence and re-orders them according to Kannada SOV grammar before passing the restructured string to the text-to-speech pipeline. The audio output the child hears in Kannada is therefore not a word-for-word rendering of the English sequence but a grammatically valid Kannada sentence, providing linguistically accurate native-language reinforcement.

\subsection{On-Device Machine Learning for Affective Computing}

Emotion recognition in children with ASD is a well-documented challenge. Difficulty identifying and labelling the facial expressions of others --- and in some cases one's own expressions --- can impair social interaction and contribute to miscommunication. Social-emotional learning interventions that use mirror-based or camera-based exercises to help children observe and name facial states have shown positive outcomes in controlled studies.

This work implements on-device emotion detection using ML Kit Face Detection combined with a MobileNetV3 classification model trained on the IIITM Face Emotion dataset. MobileNetV3 was selected for its favourable trade-off between accuracy and computational cost on mobile hardware: the model is sufficiently lightweight to run in real time on a standard Android device without requiring cloud inference, which eliminates latency, preserves privacy, and removes the dependency on network connectivity. The model is deployed with INT8 quantisation, which reduces model size and inference time at a measured accuracy cost of approximately 2.49 percentage points in weighted F1 score relative to the full-precision baseline --- a trade-off considered acceptable given the interactive, low-latency requirements of real-time emotion feedback on a mobile device.

Recent advances in lightweight deep learning architectures have demonstrated promising performance for real-time emotion recognition on mobile devices while maintaining low computational requirements~\cite{b13,b14,b15}. These developments have enabled affective computing applications to move from cloud-based environments to fully on-device deployments, improving privacy, reducing latency, and increasing accessibility.

\subsection{Gamification and Behavioural Reinforcement}

Applied Behaviour Analysis (ABA), one of the most extensively validated therapeutic frameworks for ASD, relies on the systematic use of positive reinforcement to shape target behaviours. When a desired behaviour is consistently followed by a rewarding outcome, the probability of that behaviour recurring increases. This principle underlies the gamified assessment and reward system in the present application. Correct responses in the quiz module trigger positive feedback in the form of visual reward animations and progress indicators, providing the kind of immediate, predictable reinforcement that ABA research identifies as most effective for autistic learners~\cite{b6}.

The quiz module is not merely a motivational wrapper, however. It also functions as a structured vocabulary assessment, presenting the child with matching tasks between word tiles and images or between English labels and Kannada translations. The module is differentiated by login role: therapist accounts have access to a progress dashboard that aggregates performance data across sessions, providing a data-informed record of vocabulary acquisition and response accuracy that can inform therapeutic planning.

