\section{System Architecture and Design}

\subsection{Overview}

The application is a native Android system developed in Kotlin using Jetpack Compose for the UI layer. The architecture follows a modular design in which five principal functional components --- the AAC communication grid, the bilingual sentence builder, the AR vocabulary pipeline, the emotion recognition module, and the gamified assessment module --- operate as independently deployable units sharing a common data layer. Firebase Authentication handles role-differentiated login for therapist and student accounts; Cloud Firestore persists custom vocabulary tiles and session progress data; and Firebase Storage hosts caregiver-uploaded photographs associated with custom tile entries.

\subsection{AAC Communication Grid}

The core interface is a tile-based communication grid consisting of two tile types: Word Tiles representing individual concepts, and Folder Tiles representing categories such as ``Food,'' ``Feelings,'' and ``Activities.'' This two-tier hierarchy allows the vocabulary space to scale without overwhelming a single screen. Navigation is tracked by a breadcrumb bar at the top of the interface displaying the current path (e.g., HOME $>$ FOOD), preserving the child's orientation within the vocabulary hierarchy.

Each Word Tile is colour-coded according to the Fitzgerald Key: green for verbs, yellow for people, blue for descriptive words, and orange for core vocabulary items. When a tile is tapped, it is added to the Sentence Tray at the bottom of the screen, and a Zoom Overlay animation momentarily expands the tile to full-screen size before collapsing, providing a clear perceptual confirmation of the selection. The Sentence Tray accumulates tiles until the child activates the ``Speak'' function, at which point the assembled sequence is passed to the speech synthesis pipeline.

\subsection{Bilingual Sentence Builder and Text-to-Speech Pipeline}

The speech synthesis pipeline follows a sequential, triple-reinforcement audio flow designed to support both literacy development and bilingual language acquisition:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Letter-by-letter spelling:} The English word is spelled aloud character by character before the full word is spoken (e.g., ``A-P-P-L-E''), supporting phonemic awareness.
    \item \textbf{English pronunciation:} The complete English word or sentence is spoken using Android's \texttt{TextToSpeech} engine configured for English.
    \item \textbf{Kannada pronunciation:} The SOV-reordered Kannada equivalent is spoken using the \texttt{TextToSpeech} engine configured for the Kannada locale.
\end{enumerate}

An \texttt{isSpeaking} state flag ensures that audio segments are queued sequentially and do not overlap, which is essential for children who are sensitive to auditory chaos. The SOV reordering layer identifies subject, object, and verb components in the tile sequence and restructures the token order before passing the string to Kannada TTS, producing grammatically correct output in both languages.

\subsection{AR Vocabulary Pipeline}

The AR vocabulary pipeline integrates three subsystems: Android CameraX for the live video feed, ML Kit Object Detection and Tracking (v17.0.2) for real-world object identification, and ARCore 1.40.0 for spatial anchoring of word cards in three-dimensional space.

The camera pipeline operates in Stream Mode with an \texttt{ImageAnalysis} use case at a resolution of 640$\times$480 or 1280$\times$720, selected dynamically to balance detection accuracy with battery efficiency. Multi-object detection is enabled, allowing the system to simultaneously identify and annotate multiple objects within the camera frame. A confidence threshold of 0.5 ensures that only objects identified with at least 50\% confidence trigger word card rendering, reducing the risk of spurious annotations that could constitute cognitive noise for a hypersensitive user.

When an object is detected above the confidence threshold, the pipeline proceeds as follows:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The ML Kit bounding box coordinates are mapped to ARCore anchor coordinates.
    \item An AR word card is rendered in three-dimensional space relative to the detected object's position.
    \item The \texttt{GrammarEngine.kt} module identifies the detected object's semantic category and surfaces contextually relevant verbs (e.g., ``Eat'' and ``Want'' for food-category detections).
    \item The word card and associated verb suggestions are displayed as an overlay anchored to the physical object, persisting as the device camera moves using ARCore's tracking system.
\end{enumerate}

The base object detection model is trained on the Open Images Dataset V4, a large-scale dataset spanning millions of images across thousands of categories. For Indian food items not adequately covered by the base model, supplementary fine-tuning data was drawn from the Indian Food Detection dataset available via Roboflow.

\subsection{Emotion Recognition Module}

The emotion recognition module activates the front-facing camera and processes the live feed through a two-stage pipeline. ML Kit Face Detection first locates and landmarks the face within the frame. The extracted face region is then passed to a MobileNetV3 classification model trained on the IIITM Face Emotion dataset and deployed on-device in INT8 quantised form. The model produces a probability distribution over the standard set of basic emotion categories (happy, sad, angry, surprised, fearful, disgusted, neutral), and the highest-probability label is displayed as an animated overlay on the camera feed.

All inference is performed on-device: no face images or emotion labels are transmitted to any external server. The on-device design decision was driven by three considerations: the privacy sensitivity of facial data from children, the need for low-latency real-time feedback, and the requirement that the feature remain functional in environments with unreliable internet connectivity --- a realistic constraint for many of the target users in the Indian context.

