\subsection{Gamified Assessment Module}

The quiz module presents the child with a series of vocabulary matching tasks drawn from the child's current AAC tile inventory. Task formats include image-to-word matching, English-to-Kannada translation tasks, and category-sorting exercises. Correct responses trigger a reward animation and increment the child's session score. The module adapts to the child's vocabulary by drawing questions only from tiles the child has encountered in recent sessions, ensuring that assessments are grounded in the child's current communicative vocabulary rather than in a generic item bank.

Therapist accounts have access to an analytics view that displays per-session response accuracy, word category performance breakdowns, and longitudinal progress trends across sessions. This data layer allows therapists and caregivers to observe which vocabulary categories a child is consolidating, where gaps remain, and how communication fluency is evolving over time.

\subsection{Caregiver Personalisation System}

Parents and therapists can add custom vocabulary tiles through a tile creation interface accessible via a floating action button. The creation flow prompts the user to: (1) provide the word label in English and optionally in Kannada; (2) capture or upload a photograph of the real-world object or person the tile represents; and (3) assign the tile to a category. Category assignment drives automatic Fitzgerald Key colour coding, ensuring that custom tiles are visually consistent with the standard tile library. Custom tiles are stored in Firebase Storage (photographs) and Firestore (metadata), making them device-independent and persistent across sessions on any device on which the family's account is authenticated.

\subsection{Security and Accessibility Infrastructure}

The application uses Firebase Authentication for role-differentiated access: separate credential flows for therapist and student accounts ensure that progress data and settings are appropriately scoped by role. The UI implements \texttt{navigationBarsPadding} and \texttt{statusBarsPadding} insets to ensure that interactive elements are not obscured by system gesture bars across the wide range of Android device form factors in the Indian market.

