The results indicate strong stakeholder acceptance across all evaluated dimensions. Technology-assisted learning achieved a mean score of 8.73/10, demonstrating widespread agreement that digital learning tools can positively influence educational outcomes for children with Autism Spectrum Disorder. More than 90\% of respondents assigned ratings between 8 and 10, highlighting strong confidence in technology-supported intervention approaches.

Augmented Reality learning achieved a mean score of 8.41/10. Most respondents rated the feature between 8 and 9, indicating that immersive and interactive learning environments are perceived as effective mechanisms for improving engagement and maintaining attention during educational activities.

Emotion recognition emerged as one of the highest-rated functionalities with a score of 9.23/10. The majority of respondents believed that helping children recognize and understand emotions can contribute significantly to social communication and emotional development. Similarly, the communication and AAC module also achieved a score of 9.23/10, reinforcing the importance of communication support tools for non-verbal and minimally verbal children.

Object detection activities received a mean score of 8.77/10, demonstrating stakeholder confidence in the ability of real-world object association to improve vocabulary acquisition and concept learning. The gamification module obtained a score of 9.09/10, indicating strong agreement that rewards, badges, and achievement-based activities can improve motivation and participation during learning sessions.

The application's user interface received a score of 9.18/10, suggesting that respondents considered the interface simple, accessible, and appropriate for children with ASD. Furthermore, the overall usefulness of the application received the highest evaluation score of 9.27/10, indicating strong confidence in its potential to support therapy sessions, communication development, and home-based learning.

Overall, the proposed system achieved an average evaluation score of 8.99/10 across all categories, demonstrating substantial stakeholder acceptance and validating the design objectives established during the requirement analysis phase.

\subsection{Discussion of Key Findings}
 
Among all evaluated features, communication support and emotion recognition emerged as the most important functionalities. This observation aligns with existing literature, which identifies communication difficulties and emotional awareness as two of the primary developmental challenges experienced by children with ASD. The strong ratings obtained by these modules suggest that integrating communication assistance with emotional learning may provide a more holistic intervention approach.

The positive response towards Augmented Reality and object detection activities further highlights the importance of visual and experiential learning methods. By connecting digital vocabulary elements with real-world objects, the application promotes contextual learning and strengthens word-object associations. Similarly, the high rating achieved by the gamification module indicates that reward-based learning strategies can improve motivation and encourage sustained participation during educational activities.

These findings collectively suggest that the proposed application successfully addresses multiple developmental domains simultaneously, including communication, emotional development, vocabulary acquisition, engagement, and independent learning.

