\section{Conclusion}

This paper has presented the design, architecture, and expert evaluation of a native Android application that integrates AAC communication support, AR-based real-world vocabulary learning, bilingual sentence construction in English and Kannada, on-device emotion recognition, caregiver personalisation, and gamified progress tracking within a single sensory-aware interface. The application was developed in direct response to a well-documented gap in the assistive technology landscape for Indian children with ASD: the absence of a unified, bilingual, locally contextualised tool that addresses communication, learning, and emotional development simultaneously.

The system makes several contributions that distinguish it from existing work. The bilingual sentence builder handles the structural divergence between English SVO and Kannada SOV grammar, providing linguistically accurate reinforcement in a language pair not previously addressed in the AAC literature. The AR vocabulary pipeline grounds digital word cards in detected real-world objects and extends simple object labelling with a context-aware verb suggestion engine, connecting the AAC system to the child's physical environment in a pedagogically motivated way. The caregiver personalisation system allows the vocabulary to grow with the child's individual communicative needs, using real photographs of the child's specific environment rather than generic icon sets. These capabilities, validated through structured expert feedback at two ASD clinical centres in Bengaluru, represent a combination not previously demonstrated for the Indian ASD context.

The developmental window between ages five and eight, during which the application is targeted, is broadly recognised as the period of greatest neuroplasticity for foundational literacy and communication skills. Technology-assisted interventions introduced during this window have the potential for lasting developmental impact. The present work takes a step toward making such interventions accessible, affordable, and appropriate for the linguistic and cultural realities of Indian families --- a population that has been systematically underserved by the predominantly Western, English-language AAC tools currently available.

The findings of this work are consistent with recent advances in AAC systems, assistive technologies, bilingual learning environments, and technology-enhanced interventions for children with ASD~\cite{b23,b24,b25}. The positive survey results and expert feedback indicate strong potential for the proposed platform to support communication, learning, and emotional development in a manner that is both accessible and culturally relevant to Indian families.

Future work will pursue three directions: a controlled longitudinal evaluation of communication outcomes with child participants at partnering clinical centres; extension of the bilingual engine to additional Indian regional languages including Tamil, Telugu, and Hindi; and targeted retraining of the object detection model on Indian domestic environment data to improve AR recognition accuracy for the objects most commonly encountered in the homes of the target population.

